Title: Windows distribute patched gcc 9 instead of gcc 7
Body: Fixes #288 and #175.    I finally found the cause of the bug preventing gcc-8 to link when it was installed in a folder with a space. The problem comes from `windres` which fails at executing in a folder containing a space. `windres` is called at link time by `ld` to link the resulting executable with a file called `default-manifest.o`. If this file is not present  then `ld` doesn't attempt to use it and doesn't fail. It seems this `default-manifest.o` file is not very important and according to my tests  everything works fine without it. See https://github.com/msys2/MSYS2-packages/issues/454 for details. Removing this file from the distribution actually fixes gcc-8 link and hence allow us to use gcc-8 instead of gcc-7 in the distribution.

Title: Use POSIX shared memory instead of SYSV shared memory on Linux and macOS
Body: By default Qt uses SYSV shared memory on Linux and macOS. This has several drawbacks:  - on macOS: the default size of SYSV shared memory segments is very small preventing many camera-based simulation to work out-of-the-box. We ask users to modify their system settings to work around this problem  which is not very user friendly.  - on Linux: the SYSV shared memory segments are not compatible with snap strict confinement  hence preventing us to package Webots as a snap package with strict confinement (which is better than the classic confinement).

Title: Improve linux launcher termination
Body: Related to https://github.com/omichel/robotbenchmark/issues/348:  in the streaming server application it happens that Webots launcher is killed but not the `webots-bin` process.  In the current version the termination and interruption signals are already caught and propagated to `webots-bin`  but with the current workflow it is possible that the launcher exits before the `webots-bin` child process terminates (see articles referenced just below).     Resources:  - https://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/146756/forward-sigterm-to-child-in-bash/444676#444676  - http://veithen.io/2014/11/16/sigterm-propagation.html

Title: Fixed clang format version problem
Body: Five day ago  MSYS2 upgraded clang to version 9.0.0 (and thus clang-format). Since then  the clang-format formatting on Windows is different and causes the source test to fail on travis and appveyor. I found that with clang-format 9.0.0  we should simply add an option (`AllowAllConstructorInitializersOnNextLine: false`) to fix the problem and have the same formatting as previously. However  this option is not recognized by versions of clang-format older than 9.0.0  causing a run-time error. Therefore  we have to handle two different `.clang-format` configuration files: one for Windows with MSYS2 and the other for Linux  macOS and Appveyor (which uses an older version of clang-format).

Title: Fixed extern controllers on snap
Body: Fixes #950.    This PR makes it easy to run extern controllers with the snap package (no need to be administrator). Basically  the webots launcher and libController were modified so that the snap version of webots can run extern controllers without any special setup. The user may override the `WEBOTS_TMPDIR` and/or `TMPDIR` environment variables before launching webots and the extern controllers if needed. Otherwise  they will be automatically setup to a default value (`$SNAP_USER_COMMON/tmp` = `~/snap/webots/common/tmp` for the snap version or `/tmp` for the non-snap version) that guarantees it will work smoothly with both the snap and non-snap versions of webots.    Additionally  the launcher now cleans-up the temporary folder and pipe files in case webots crashed without cleaning them up.    The new documentation page is available here for review: https://cyberbotics.com/doc/guide/installation-procedure?version=fix-extern-controller-on-snap    Finally  once this PR is merged  the https://cyberbotics.com/download page should be updated to add a link to the [Webots page](https://snapcraft.io/webots) on the snap store.    Also  as soon as we get an answer from https://lauchpad.net  we will be able to change the snap author from "Olivier Michel" to "Cyberbotics".

Title: Feature Mesh Node
Body: **Description**  This PR implements the `Mesh` node.    **Related Issues**  This pull-request fixes the first part of #1396    **Tasks**  Add the list of tasks of this PR.    - [x] Add Mesh node.    - [x] Add WREN part.    - [x] Add ODE part.    - [x] Merge meshes if more than one mesh is in the file.    - [x] Create a commun parent class for IdnexedFaceSet and Mesh.    - [x] Add the `meshes` folder to the concept of Webots project.    - [x] Sample: https://cyberbotics.com/doc/guide/samples-geometries?version=feature-mesh-node#geometric_primitives-wbt    - [x] Recompile assimp for Mac including importers.    - [x] Documentation:      - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/node-chart?version=feature-mesh-node      - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/mesh?version=feature-mesh-node    - [x] Test.      - [x] Pen.      - [x] DistanceSensor.    - [x] Changelog.    As this PR is already quite big  I will limit the following features in the first step:    - no crease angle field for now.    - support 'only' the following formats (we may easily add some more in the future if needed):      - blend      -  dae      - fbx      - obj      - stl    - I deliberately didn't add a mesh in the physics_primitives.wbt to avoid encouraging the user to use Meshes as bounding objects.    Except this  everything will be functional (including streaming server).

Title: Add Lookup Table Getter to Controller API
Body: **Description**  The objective is to allow the user to read values from the lookup table from the controller API.    **Related Issues**  Related to issue #1603. Also  this PR is split from #1610.    **Tasks**    - [x] DistanceSensor (done in 7299c34)      - [x] Getter for lookup table size and values      - [x] Add support for languages other than C      - [x] Add tests      - [x] Add documentation - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/distancesensor?version=feature-lookup-table    - [x] Accelerometer      - [x] Getter for lookup table size and values      - [x] Add support for languages other than C      - [x] Add tests      - [x] Add documentation - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/accelerometer?version=feature-lookup-table    - [x] Compass      - [x] Getter for lookup table size and values      - [x] Add support for languages other than C      - [x] Add tests      - [x] Add documentation - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/compass?version=feature-lookup-table    - [x] Gyro      - [x] Getter for lookup table size and values      - [x] Add support for languages other than C      - [x] Add tests      - [x] Add documentation - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/gyro?version=feature-lookup-table    - [x] InertialUnit      - [x] Getter for lookup table size and values      - [x] Add support for languages other than C      - [x] Add tests      - [x] Add documentation - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/inertialunit?version=feature-lookup-table    - [x] LightSensor      - [x] Getter for lookup table size and values      - [x] Add support for languages other than C      - [x] Add tests      - [x] Add documentation - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/lightsensor?version=feature-lookup-table    - [x] TouchSensor      - [x] Getter for lookup table size and values      - [x] Add support for languages other than C      - [x] Add tests      - [x] Add documentation - https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/touchsensor?version=feature-lookup-table    - [x] Test the interface for languages other than C (exhaustive tests are performed only on C API  for other languages only "representative" functions are tested  e.g. obtaining array result from `wb_distance_sensor_get_lookup_table`)      - [x] C++ is considered to be working fine if Python API works      - [x] Python      - [x] ROS (compiled `webots_ros` and patched to support `get_float_array.srv`)      - [x] Java      - [x] Matlab (tested on R2019b)    - [x] Ignore `wb_*_get_lookup_table_size()` in:      - [x] Matlab        - [x] Python       - [x] Java       - [x] ROS and      - [x] documentation.    **Additional context**  Verification controller:  ```c  #include <stdio.h>  #include <webots/distance_sensor.h>  #include <webots/robot.h>    #define TIME_STEP 64    void print_lookup_table(WbDeviceTag tag) {    int size = wb_distance_sensor_get_lookup_table_size(tag);    const double* lookup = wb_distance_sensor_get_lookup_table(tag);    printf("Number of items in lookup table %d\n"  size);    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++)      printf("[#%d] %f %f %f\n"  i  lookup[i*3]  lookup[i*3+1]  lookup[i*3+2]);  }    int main(int argc  char *argv[]) {    wb_robot_init();    WbDeviceTag ds = wb_robot_get_device("ps7");    print_lookup_table(ds);    wb_robot_cleanup();    return 0;  }  ```

Title: Allow Basic URDF Export
Body: **Description**  According to the discussion  we should rather convert the node structure to URDF and publish transforms through `robot_state_publisher`. Therefore  this PR aims to allow export of stripped URDF version for `robot_state_publisher`. Extended  but still stripped version will be allowed later for RViz visualization.    URDF + `robot_state_publisher` vs publishing TF messages directly:  - Having URDF is much more flexible:    - can be used to publish TF messages with `robot_state_publisher`     - can be used to visualize in RViz2     - can be used with MoveIt     - transfer to real-robot is much faster (just copy-paste generated URDF file)     - part of maintenance (e.g. `robot_state_publisher`) is done by ROS community and    - it makes the implementation of TF messages easier for ROS1 (just publish joint states)  - Publishing TF messages directly is faster and simpler to use:    - no overhead caused by `robot_state_publisher` (mostly caused by exchanging the messages)     - no need to start another process `robot_state_publisher`.    **Related Issues**  Closes #1603. Replaces #1610    **Tasks**  - [x] Determine what part of URDF `<link />` is relevant. (A) None  only joints are relevant for transformations. `<link />` should just exist as placeholders.  - [x] Determine mappings from Webots joints to URDF `<joint />`. (A) `WbHinge` --> `<joint type="continious" />`  `WbSlider` --> `<joint type="prismatic" />` and link-to-link --> `<joint type="fixed" />`.  - [x] Create converter for joints:    - [x] link-to-link --> `<joint type="fixed" />` (only where needed)    - [x] `WbHinge` --> `<joint type="continious" />`    - [x] `WbSlider` --> `<joint type="prismatic" />`  - [x] The tree is currently huge  we don't need everything  ignore irrelevant nodes:    - [x] Children of the last node that has `name` parameter (this may be bad later for exporting bounding objects)    - [x] Physics    - [x] Squash all  non-device  solid-to-solid nodes under the same `<link />`  - [x] Add API support    - [x] C    - [x] C++    - [x] Python    - [x] Java    - [x] MATLAB (not tested)    - [x] ROS    - [x] Other  - [x] Documentation (https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/robot?version=feature-urdf-export&tab-language=c#wb_robot_get_urdf)  - [x] Unit tests  - [x] Improve URDF formatting    - [x] Avoid new lines when unnecessary    - [x] Fix NULL artifacts in URDF file  - [x] Verify why adding a tool to UR5 crashes the simulation   - [x] Test with a few models    - [x] E-Puck (because it has hinge joints without limits)    - [x] E-Puck + ROS2     - [x] UR5e (because it has hinge joints with limits)    - [x] UR5e + ROS2     - [x] Tiago++ (because it has slider joint)    - [x] UR5e + tool (to test if slot is handled properly)    - [x] UR5e + tool + ROS2     **Additional context**  Useful commands:  ```  ./webots --minimize > /tmp/test.xml  check_urdf /tmp/test.xml  urdf_to_graphiz /tmp/test.xml  ros2 run robot_state_publisher robot_state_publisher /tmp/test.xml  ```  (`/tmp/test.xml` is URDF file  `.xml` extension is temporary to benefit from the syntax highlighters)

Title: Renamed webots exe to webots bin exe
Body: Fixes #137 as it was reported again by several users.  This fix simply renames `webots.exe` to `webots-bin.exe`.  It fixes the problem of typing `webots` in a DOS CMD console.  Previously  this was launching `webots.exe` directly and was causing problems with JPEG textures as explained in #137.  Now  it launches a different `webots.exe` which is a simple launcher for `webots-bin.exe`.  `webots.exe` sets the `PATH` environment variable appropriately and starts `webots-bin.exe`.  As a consequence  Webots launches nicely and the JPEG textures bug doesn't show up any more.  It will still show up if the user type `webots-bin` in the DOS CMD console  which is less likely.

Title: Fix nested DEF USE nodes
Body: **Description**  If USE node B has a DEF ancestor A  then USE node A is not updated when DEF node B changes.  Sample world:  ```  Solid {    children [      Transform {        children [          DEF B Shape {            appearance Appearance {              material Material {              }            }            geometry Box {              size 0.1 0.1 0.1          }        ]      }      DEF A Transform {        translation 0.4 0 0        children [          USE B        ]      }    ]    boundingObject USE A  }  ```    **Related Issues**  This pull-request fixes issue #1538.      **Tasks**  * [x] Update DEF ancestor of USE nodes on field change  * [x] Check if USE node is up-to-date before forwarding the field changes  * [x] Add test    Second task fixes a crash when inserting a Material node into the following DEF A Appearance:  ```  DEF G Group {    children [      DEF S Shape {        appearance DEF A Appearance {        }      }      USE S    ]  }  USE G  ```

Title: Fix various crashes related to PROTO template regenerator fields
Body: Fix #1854:  if the PROTO node that is going to be converted is contained in a PROTO template regenerator field  the parent node and parent field pointers will become invalid just after deleting the previous node and will cause memory issues when inserting the new one.  To overcome this issue  the template regeneration triggered by the delete should be blocked (same approach also used for example in the `WbSceneTree::reset` method). So that then PROTO will only be regenerated once after the new node is imported.

Title: Add Transformation Tree Getter to Controller API
Body:
**Description**  Add controller API support to read TF tree of the robot.    **Related Issues**  Closes #1603    **Tasks**    - [x] Create `tf_tree_print()` to debug the results    - [ ] Read transformation tree in `WbRobot.cpp`      - [x] Find and send relevant primitives (joints and links) in the robot tree      - [x] Rotation and translation in respect to the parent node      - [x] Store relevant HingeJointParameters       - [x] Add support for different joint implementations. Find solid endpoints and continue parsing the tree.        - [x] WbSliderJoint        - [x] WbHingeJoint2        - [x] BallJoint        - [x] WbHingeJoint      - [x] Compress the tf (we don't care about link<->link  only device<->joint)      - [ ] Verify if there are relevant and unhandled nodes (if it works for e-puck doesn't mean it will work for the other robots)    - [x] Add API for controller      - [x] Parse the transformation tree      - [x] Expose getter function      - [x] Clean the tree      - [x] Add Python support to be able to test it with `webots_ros2`    - [ ] Add support for languages other than C    - [ ] Add documentation    - [ ] Add unit tests    - [x] Shift origin of joint in case the parent is node is considered irrelevant    - [ ] Test      - [x] WbHingeJoint      - [ ] WbHingeJoint2      - [ ] BallJoint      - [ ] WbSliderJoint    **Additional context**    <details><summary>Controller for the tree printing and visualization (.dot)</summary>    ```c  #include <stdio.h>  #include <webots/robot.h>    #define TIME_STEP 64    static void tf_make_dot_rec(FILE *f  WbTransformNodeObject *root) {    // Generate .dot file. You can visualize it later as:    // $ dot -Tpng /tmp/robot.dot > /tmp/robot.png && xdg-open /tmp/robot.png    for (int i = 0; i < root->n_children; i++) {      fprintf(f  "%d -> %d;
"  root->id  root->children[i]->id);      if (root->children[i]->type == WB_TF_NODE_LINK)        fprintf(f  "%d [shape=box];
"  root->children[i]->id);      tf_make_dot_rec(f  root->children[i]);    }  }    static void tf_make_dot(WbTransformNodeObject *root) {    FILE *f;    f = fopen("/tmp/robot.dot"  "w");    fprintf(f  "digraph graphname {
");    fprintf(f  "%d [shape=box];
"  root->id);    tf_make_dot_rec(f  root);    fprintf(f  "}
");    fclose(f);  }    static void tf_print_details(WbTransformNodeObject *root) {    if (root->type == WB_TF_NODE_LINK) {      if (root->parent == NULL)        printf("From root node to [%d] %s
"  root->id  root->name);      else        printf("From [%d] %s to [%d] %s
"  (root->parent)->id  (root->parent)->name  root->id  root->name);      printf("Rotation matrix = [
");      printf("  %f %f %f
"  root->rotation[0]  root->rotation[1]  root->rotation[2]);      printf("  %f %f %f
"  root->rotation[3]  root->rotation[4]  root->rotation[5]);      printf("  %f %f %f
"  root->rotation[6]  root->rotation[7]  root->rotation[8]);      printf("]
");      printf("Translation = [ %f %f %f ]
"  root->translation[0]  root->translation[1]  root->translation[2]);      printf("
");    }      for (int i = 0; i < root->n_children; i++)      tf_print_details(root->children[i]);  }    static void tf_tree_print(WbTransformNodeObject *root  int level) {    for (int i = 0; i < level; i++)      printf("      |");    if (root->type == WB_TF_NODE_JOINT)      printf("----(%d)
"  root->id);    else      printf("----[%d] %s
"  root->id  root->name);        for (int i = 0; i < root->n_children; i++)      tf_tree_print(root->children[i]  level+1);  }    int main(int argc  char *argv[]) {    wb_robot_init();      wb_robot_step(TIME_STEP);    WbTransformNodeObject* tf_tree = wb_robot_get_transform_tree();      tf_tree_print(tf_tree  0);    tf_print_details(tf_tree);    tf_make_dot(tf_tree);      wb_robot_cleanup();    return 0;  }  ```  </details>      <details><summary>Verification controller in Python</summary>    ```py  from controller import Robot      def tf_print_details(root):      if root.get_type() == Robot.TF_NODE_LINK:          if not root.get_parent():              print(f'From root node to [{root.get_id()}] {root.get_name()}')          else:              print(f'From [{root.get_id()}] {root.get_name()} to [{root.get_parent().get_id()}] {root.get_parent().get_name()}')          print('Rotation matrix = [')          print(f'  {root.get_rotation()[0]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[1]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[2]:.3f}')          print(f'  {root.get_rotation()[3]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[4]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[5]:.3f}')          print(f'  {root.get_rotation()[6]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[7]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[8]:.3f}')          print(']')          print(f'Translation = [ {root.get_translation()[0]:.3f} {root.get_translation()[1]:.3f} {root.get_translation()[2]:.3f} ]')          print('')        for child in root.get_children():          tf_print_details(child)      robot = Robot()    timestep = int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())  robot.step(timestep)  tree = robot.getTransformTree()  tf_print_details(tree)  ```  </details>

Title: Add no rendering flag
Body: **Description**  This PR adds `--no-rendering` which hides 3D view.    **Related Issues**  Implements #2245    **Tasks**    - [x] Basic implementation    - [x] Full implementation      - [x] Configuration should be read/written to file      - [x] Configuration should be accessible through `--no-rendering` flag      - [x] Buttons in play menu      - [x] Menu bar        - [x] Simulation > Show/Hide        - [x] View > Scene Interactions > Disable 3D View      - [x] <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>4</kbd>      - [x] Supervisor API       - [x] Movie recording shortcuts    - [x] Add GUI icon      - [x] Improve icon resolution and shape     - [x] Implement backward compatibility strategy      - [x] Command line      - [ ] Supervisor (this will fail  open for discussion)      - [x] From file    - [x] Add to changelog    - [x] Change documentation    **New behavior**    - Case A    - before `webots --mode=run`    - now `webots --mode=fast`  - Case B    - before `webots --mode=fast`    - now `webots --mode=fast --no-rendering`  - Case C    - before you want to use mode `realtime` without 3D view (you cannot)    - now `webots --mode=realtime --no-rendering`  - Case D    - before <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>4</kbd> to start fast mode    - now <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>3</kbd> to enable new fast mode and <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>4</kbd> to toggle 3D view  - Case E    - before `wb_supervisor_simulation_get_mode()` returns `WB_SUPERVISOR_SIMULATION_MODE_RUN` or `WB_SUPERVISOR_SIMULATION_MODE_FAST`    - now `wb_supervisor_simulation_get_mode()` returns only `WB_SUPERVISOR_SIMULATION_MODE_FAST`    **Backward incompatible**  - `webots --mode=run`    - deprecation warning + falling back to `fast` mode  - `WB_SUPERVISOR_SIMULATION_MODE_RUN` from Supervisoir API is deleted

Title: Get quaternion from InertialUnit
Body: This PR adds support to the `InertialUnit` node that allows retrieval of quaternions. This allows us to avoid gimbal-lock and to be closer to the real sensor implementation. It also fixes orientation in ROS.    **Physical Sensor Example**  I used an MPU6050 sensor (driver implementation) as an example:  - quaternions are directly returned from the sensor: https://github.com/ElectronicCats/mpu6050/blob/845ee3978b6554967e510d8dd5f74c2c764908e3/src/MPU6050_6Axis_MotionApps20.h#L438  - roll/pitch/yaw are computed from the quaternions: https://github.com/ElectronicCats/mpu6050/blob/845ee3978b6554967e510d8dd5f74c2c764908e3/src/MPU6050_6Axis_MotionApps20.h#L547  - gimbal-lock issue: https://github.com/ElectronicCats/mpu6050/blob/845ee3978b6554967e510d8dd5f74c2c764908e3/examples/MPU6050_DMP6_ESPWiFi/MPU6050_DMP6_ESPWiFi.ino#L103    **Non-related fixes**  - PointStamped is published by GPS instead of Point. This also fixes ROS tests.    **Documentation**  https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/inertialunit?version=feature-inertial-unit-quaternion    **ROS Objective**  The ROS layer should be changed  so RVIz and Webots orientation match if the coordinate system is ENU:  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2135826/97864165-77b18a80-1d08-11eb-86ab-d0b3aa8ea41f.png)    **Related Issues**  https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros/issues/37  https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros/pull/38/    **Tasks**    - [x] Basic implementation    - [x] Decide on how the lookup table should be implemented    - [x] Add getter for `noise` parameter    - [x] Python/Java/Matlab    - [x] Documentation    - [x] Document gimbal-lock case    - [x] Changelog

Title: Add recognition and segmentation functionalities to default robot window
Body: Address #2400: add checkboxed in the Camera tab of the default robot window to enabled/disable recognition and segmentation functionalities.  These checkboxes are displayed only if the `Recognition` node is available  respectively `Recognition.segmentation` field is set to TRUE.    ![Screenshot from 2020-11-04 13-03-40](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5910449/98109668-38b53d80-1e9e-11eb-82b6-c3915843f9bf.png)      Tasks:  * [x] add Camera API function `wb_camera_recognition_is_segmentation_enabled` to check if the segmentation has been enabled from the controller or not: this is needed to update the checkbox in the robot window  * [x] add checkboxes and related code to show the recognition and segmentation status and update it when changed from the  controller  * [x] fix internal status of segmentation enabled/disabled in the libController that was not matching Webots after disabling the camera recognition functionality    The `wb_camera_recognition_is_segmentation_enabled` C API function is needed internally.  We can decide if we want to make it public  documented and available on all the APIs or if we want to keep it private and move it in a `camera_private.h` header file.

Title: Export node as a string
Body: Another feature to allow users to do reinforcement learning easier. By getting a string of a node users can use it in conjunction with `wb_supervisor_field_import_mf_node_from_string`/`wb_supervisor_field_import_sf_node_from_string` to duplicate environments.    This PR implements:  - `wb_supervisor_node_export_string(node)` which returns content of the node as a string.    **Tasks**  - [x] Add `wb_supervisor_node_export_string`   - Add support for other languages:    - [x] C++    - [x] Python    - [x] Java    - [x] Matlab    - [x] ROS  - [x] Documentation  - [x] Tests  - [x] ROS tests  - [x] Changelog  - [x] Controller.def + WbLanguage.cpp

Title: Implement node state list
Body: We want to add two supervisor functions:  - `wb_supervisor_node_save_state(node  state_name)`: saves node's state (like translation  rotation...) and all children of the node with name `state_name` (string)  - `wb_supervisor_node_load_state(node  state_name)` loads node's state (like translation  rotation...) and all children of the node with name `state_name` (string)    This will allow a partial restart of the world  allowing us to run multiple reinforcement learning environments in a single instance of Webots.    This PR also fixes #2759    **Documentation**  https://www.cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=feature-state-list#wb_supervisor_node_save_state    https://www.cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=feature-state-list#resetreload-matrix    **Tasks**  - [x] Add  `state_name` to `WbNode::reset` and `WbNode::save`  - [x] Add Supervisor C API  - Add support for other languages:    - [x] C++    - [x] Python    - [x] Java    - [x] Matlab    - [x] ROS  - [x] Documentation  - [x] Check `mPreviousRotation = mSavedRotations[id];` in `WbSolid.cpp`  - [x] Tests  - [x] ROS tests  - [x] Controller.def + WbLanguage.cpp  - [x] Changelog          **Samples**  <details>  <summary>Sample controller</summary>    ```python  import time  from controller import Supervisor    robot = Supervisor()  timestep = int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())    left_motor = robot.getDevice('left wheel motor')  right_motor = robot.getDevice('right wheel motor')  left_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  right_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  left_motor.setVelocity(2)  right_motor.setVelocity(2)      target_node = robot.getFromDef('TARGET_NODE')  for _ in range(50): robot.step(timestep)  target_node.saveState('my_state')  time.sleep(0.5)    for _ in range(50): robot.step(timestep)  target_node.saveState('my_state2')  time.sleep(0.5)    for _ in range(50): robot.step(timestep)  target_node.loadState('my_state2')  robot.step(timestep)  time.sleep(0.5)    left_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  right_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  left_motor.setVelocity(2)  right_motor.setVelocity(2)    for _ in range(50): robot.step(timestep)  target_node.loadState('my_state')  robot.step(timestep)  time.sleep(0.5)    for _ in range(50): robot.step(timestep)  left_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  right_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  left_motor.setVelocity(2)  right_motor.setVelocity(2)    target_node.loadState('__init__')    while robot.step(timestep) != -1:      pass  ```    </details>      **Description**  |  | **Reload** | **Reset from UI** | **Reset from Supervisor** | **Load node's state from Supervisor** | **Reset Title: TransmissionJoint specifications
Body: Proposition for the specifications of the `TransmissionJoint`:    `TransmissionJoint` derived from `HingeJoint`    ```  TransmissionJoint {    field SFNode  jointParameters2  NULL   # { HingeJointParameters  PROTO } (driven side)  required    field SFFloat backlash          0      # (-inf  inf)    field SFFloat multiplier        1      # (-inf  inf)  required    field SFNode startPoint         NULL   # {Solid  Slot  PROTO}  }  ```    for **classic gear**:  - the axis of jointParameters and jointParameters2 should match.  - multiplier should be negative    from ODE standpoint  nothing special  we can feed the multiplier as a ratio directly.    for **chain drive**:    - the axis of jointParameters and jointParameters2 should match.  - multiplier should be positive    from ODE standpoint  chain drive transmission requires the radii of the two wheels so in practice we impose: `radius1 = 1` and `radius2 = multiplier`.    for **bevel gears**:  - the axis of jointParameters and jointParameters2 should differ.  - ~~the multiplier should be negative.~~    ODE doesn't have a way of specifying the ratio for bevel gears  it's inferred from the provided axis.    Implementation notes:   - the two axis must intersect  show warning otherwise. ODE accepts it anyway but the results are meaningless.  - bevel gear is consistent with how it's defined in ODE  but not ideal from a user perspective as the multiplier is inferred from the axis. So webots documentation should clarify how the multiplier is inferred under the hood and that the provided value isn't being enforced. As it stands  this type of joint wouldn't be easy to use in practice.

Title: Significantly simplify the usage of the ros controller
Body: This PR significantly simplifies the usage of the `ros` controller:  - Integrates `ros_control` (the `--use-ros-control` flag) to allow usage of a differential drive  joint state publisher  trajectory follower  and other controllers.  - Adds the `--auto-publish` flag that automatically enables all sensors and creates necessary topics.  - Adds the `robot_description` ROS param which contains the robot's URDF (necessary for many ROS packages).    **Impact**  Take [the Pioneer controller](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros/blob/master/src/pioneer3at.cpp) from the `webots_ros` package as an example. The controller with over 300 lines of code is not needed anymore. Furthermore  to simplify the controller  we "cheated" by calculating odometry from GPS and IMU. There is no way something like that would work in the real world. The odometry is now calculated from the wheel encoders.    **Tasks**  - [x] Proof of concept  - [x] Test with differential drive    - [x] We need `robot_state_publisher` here. `Robot description couldn't be retrieved from param server.`   - [ ] ~~Test with MoveIt~~ (I think it is better to finish this in another PR)  - [x] Rethink namespaces (e.g. `/robot_description`  URDF prefix...)  - [x] Document  - [x] Changelog     **Useful commands**  ```bash  rosrun controller_manager controller_manager list  ```

Title: Fix update of supervisor field count
Body: Fix #1519: notify the supervisor controllers when the size of a MF field that is cached changed so that the size in the libController can be updated.    _Changes to existing messages_  Previously the MF field count was correctly updated only for MFNode fields when a node was removed.  To avoid duplicating the update  I changed the `C_SUPERVISOR_NODE_REMOVE_NODE` message so that it just deletes any cached instance of the deleted node. But the field count will be updated using the new `C_SUPERVISOR_FIELD_COUNT_CHANGED` messsage.  Similarly  when importing a node from a supervisor  Webots returned immediately the number of imported nodes to update the cached field count. For MFNode fields this return message has been removed and replaced by the new `C_SUPERVISOR_FIELD_COUNT_CHANGED`.

Title: HingeJointWithBacklash proto to model effect of backlash
Body: **EDIT: This information is outdated  see comments below.**    # Specifications   For the purpose of modeling mechanical backlash in Webots  in #2756 the option to introduce ODE's transmission joint was considered but this approach suffers from some drawbacks. Most notably  as it relies on the contact between the two wheels to  transmit the torque  deviations between input and output are introduced due to the effect of CFM at the transmission level  and these errors accumulate over time which makes this approach undesirable for the current objective.    The second more promising approach is to model backlash by extending the HingeJoint class and relying on minStop maxStop to achieve the desired effect.     ```  HingeJoint {    # current fields    field MFNode  device            [ ]   # {RotationalMotor  PositionSensor  Brake  PROTO}    field SFFloat position          0     # [0  inf)    # added fields      field SFFloat backlash          0     # [0  inf)    field SFFloat gearMass          0     # [0  inf)    field SFNode  startPoint        NULL  # {Transform} it's only for visualizing the gear  }  ```    # Preliminary result  The following videos show the results that can be obtained using the proposed approach and are obtained by cascading two HingeJoints. In **red** is shown the behavior of a classic HingeJoint (with no backlash) whereas in **blue** the case with a very large (0.2) backlash  just to make things more evident. Both motors are given the same command.    No backlash  both pendulums (single hinge and cascaded hinge) behave the same    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/109315387-c69ca600-784a-11eb-9f55-1d27f9743138.mp4    Without any gravity:    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/109310957-7707ab80-7845-11eb-9d8b-be487de20f62.mp4    With gravity:    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/109311012-8a1a7b80-7845-11eb-8b38-72ca8889ebb6.mp4

Title: Rework static proto tag logic
Body: **Description**  The current `static` tag can be somewhat misleading as typically it isn't mandatory (but suggested as an optimization) but not putting it can however lead to results such as in #2852 where the lack of the tag makes it misbehave with respect to restarts.    As suggested  the `static` behavior should be made the default case and instead a `nonDeterministic` tag is added for situations where multiple instances of a PROTO are meant to generate different results even when they have the same parameters (typically when randomness is involved).    The conversion steps undertaken are:  1. Filtering of the PROTO files that contain any of the keywords: time  seed  random  ```  projects/samples/robotbenchmark/pit_escape/protos/Pit.proto  projects/samples/rendering/protos/PingPongBallScaled.proto  projects/robots/saeon/protos/Altino.proto  projects/robots/kinematics/tinkerbots/protos/TinkerbotsAxle.proto  projects/objects/factory/conveyors/protos/ConveyorPlatform.proto  projects/objects/factory/conveyors/protos/ConveyorBelt.proto  projects/objects/trees/protos/SimpleTree.proto           <-- context.id based  projects/objects/trees/protos/Forest.proto               <-- time-based  projects/objects/floors/protos/UnevenTerrain.proto       <-- time-based  projects/objects/buildings/protos/StripBuilding.proto    <-- time-based  projects/samples/robotbenchmark/inverted_pendulum/protos/InvertedPendulumBenchmark.proto  projects/objects/factory/pallet/protos/WoodenPalletStack.proto <-- context.id based  projects/objects/buildings/protos/RandomBuilding.proto   <-- context.id based  projects/default/protos/SumoInterface.proto  projects/objects/balls/protos/RobocupSoccerBall.proto  projects/objects/balls/protos/Ball.proto  projects/bounding_objects/protos/PipeBoundingObject.proto <-- default seed  tests/protos/protos/TemplateStatic.proto            <-- default seed   tests/protos/protos/TemplateNonStatic.proto         <-- time-based  tests/api/protos/NonStaticSupervisor.proto          <-- generates a different file every time (non-random based)  projects/vehicles/protos/range_rover/RangeRoverSportSVR.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/mercedes_benz/MercedesBenzSprinter.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/tesla/TeslaModel3.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/toyota/ToyotaPrius.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/citroen/CitroenCZero.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/generic/Truck.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/generic/Bus.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/generic/Tractor.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/lincoln/LincolnMKZ.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/abstract/Car.proto  projects/vehicles/protos/bmw/BmwX5.proto  ```  2. Manual check and `nonDeterministic` tag attribution if appropriate  3. removal of `static` tag  4. adjustment to the code    ~~The PR also contains a script to add/remove/replace tags as well as filter PROTO files them based on keyword or tag. In practice it didn't need to be this convoluted but it's made anyway at this point.~~  EDIT: if necessary  the script can still be access before commit 63688b5.    **Related Issues**  This pull-request addresses issue #2852

Title: Add wb_supervisor_node_get_pose function
Body: Often  users ask for an easy way to get a relative translation and rotation between two objects. This function resolves that issue.    Furthermore  this function is more efficient than manually calculating transformation between two objects as everything is done in a single request (compared to 4 requests otherwise  2 x (orientation + position)).    **Documentation**  https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=feature-relative-pose    **Tasks**  - [x] Add Supervisor C API  - Add support for other languages:    - [x] C++    - [x] Python    - [x] Java    - [x] Matlab    - [x] ROS  - [x] Documentation  - [x] Tests  - [x] Check scale  - [x] ROS tests  - [x] Controller.def + WbLanguage.cpp  - [x] Changelog    **Test**  ```python  from controller import Supervisor      def check(a  b):      assert abs(a - b) < 0.005  f'{a} != {b}'      robot = Supervisor()  while robot.step(int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())) != -1:      pose = robot.getSelf().getPose(robot.getRoot())      # pose = robot.getSelf().getPose()      orientation = robot.getSelf().getOrientation()      position = robot.getSelf().getPosition()            for i  j in enumerate([0  1  2  4  5  6  8  9  10]):          check(pose[j]  orientation[i])            check(pose[3]  position[0])      check(pose[7]  position[1])      check(pose[11]  position[2])  ```

Title: Hotfix lib controller update after reset
Body: Fix #2992: when the simulation is reset  all the pending answers to the controllers were also reset including the fields and nodes updates due to the nodes deleted during the reset.  But if the controller is not restarted  we should not reset the pending answers because the controller is still running and it is still waiting for these messages.    The new message to update the fields count in the libController has been added in R2021b.  Some workarounds exists to prevent Webots to crash that can be applied on R2021a rev1.

Title: Feature robocup controllers
Body: I will continue the development of the referee on this branch  which is more convenient to run the tests. Once everything works  we could merge it to the Webots repository.    ### List of the bugs appearing through automated testing  - [x] Time management has to be updated    - Currently not guaranteeing that each step is not faster than...    - Real time waited is longer if the simulator can't match the real_time_factor in average  - [ ] Scoring goals from the different kind of Game Interruptions    - See all 'scoring' scenarios in 'game_interruptions'  - [x] Scoring goals from KickOff    - See 'game_phases/kick_off/'  scenarios 2 and 4  - [x] Penalty when opponent enters center circle while ball is not in play    - See 'game_phases/kick_off/'  scenarios 1 and 2  - [x] Dropped ball not implemented    - See 'game_phases/dropped_ball'  - [x] Illegally positioned robots are not penalized in SET after a goal    - See 'game_phases/repositioning'  - [ ] Problem on the INITIAL duration of the second half-time    - After 17 real-time seconds state has not changed (real_time factor 0.1)  see above    - Tested separately  even 30 minutes of simulated time after (5 minutes real-time)  state still hasn't changed (with default world)    - This problem impacts 'game_phases/second_half'  'results/win' and  'results/draw'  - [x] Robots staying out of the turf for more than 20 seconds are not penalized    - See 'misc_fouls/leaving_field'  - [ ] Inactive goalies are not penalized    - See 'misc_fouls/inactive_goalie'  - [x] Robot falling partially on the opponent side in the SET phase is not penalized    - See 'positioning/ready' (and issue 26)  - [ ] Robots might receive a penalty for being outside of the field during SET after the Autoref sent a PLAYING message to the GameController which leads to robots being sometime penalized at the start of PLAYING.    - This one is a little bit tricky because it might involve the order in which actions are applied in the GameController side.    - See 'positioning/initial' (it has been updated for clarifying the bug)    ### List of the bugs appearing through manual testing  - [ ] Transition to PLAYING from SET is sometimes failing after a goal or after 1st half  - [ ] For penalty shootouts:    - Ball is placed on the center circle  not on the penalty mark    - The transition between the states is not always working automatically    - End of the game is not detected

Title: Recursively search for finalized PROTO node
Body: Fix #3034:  fix the search for PROTO parameter node instance considering only one nested layer.  So accessing parameters of multiple nested PROTO nodes were not correctly handled causing assertion failures and crashes due to request of physical properties to non-finalized intermediate nodes.    This will be the simpler solution for users because they do not need to know the internal sub PROTO node definitions.  However  it is faster to already get the parameter node instance (or the closest node as possible) from the robot controller.

Title: Fix incorrect device limit constraints in Hinge2Joint and BallJoint
Body: **Related Issues**  This pull-request fixes issue #2823.    **Description**  As mentioned in issue #2823  device position limits ( `maxPosition` and `minPosition` on `device2`) appear to be checked against `position` field of `jointParameters` instead of `jointParameters2`.    According to the ODE documentation  this is said about hinge2joint    > Axis 1 can have joint limits and a motor  axis 2 can only have a motor.     To my understanding  joint limits refers to `minStop` and `maxStop` whereas in this particular case we're talking about _motor limits_  which I believe axis2 can have independently to axis1 and leads me to believe that issue #2823 is indeed a bug.    The bug stems from 2 factors:  - In [updateMinAndMaxPosition](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/c0ce8250876997125c4decbeed48bf0f98e39e0b/src/webots/nodes/WbMotor.cpp#L175) no distinction between the axis is made and `jointParameters` is always picked.  - In [WbJointDevice](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/c0ce8250876997125c4decbeed48bf0f98e39e0b/src/webots/nodes/WbJointDevice.cpp#L51-L61) the attribution of `mPositionIndex` occurs only in the `postFinalize` step whereas [updateMinAndMaxPosition](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/c0ce8250876997125c4decbeed48bf0f98e39e0b/src/webots/nodes/WbMotor.cpp#L99) is called in the `preFinalize` one meaning that it would always default to the first axis anyway.    Technically after fixing the first bug it would've sufficed to call `updateMinAndMaxPosition` in `postFinalize` instead of `preFinalize` to achieve the same result  but the proposed solution seems more consistent with the rest of the code (to me at least).

Title: Addition of coupled motors
Body: **Description**  This PR introduces the ability to control multiple motors  that share the same name  at the same time.    **Working principle**  - Webots side  each motor keeps track of all other motors that have the same name as itself (based on `cMotors`). They all need to have this list because in principle any of them could be directly called (if `get_device_by_index` is used  if `get_device` is used  it will usually always be the first one)  - Whenever an API call is made  for e.g.  `wb_motor_set_velocity`  the motor under question handles the message and also relays the same command to its siblings  if any. Each will adapt this command according to their own `multiplier`.  - No changes to the tag assignment/indexing logic to maintain compatibility    **Tasks**    - [x] Core functionality      - [x] velocity control      - [x] torque control      - [x] position control    - [x] Demo    - [x] Unit test    - [x] Documentation    - [x] Cleanup

Title: Fix incorrect resetting of Transform
Body: **Description**  As surfaced in #3051  under certain conditions the resetting (from GUI or from supervisor) does not appear to be working.   In some cases the objects don't return to their initial position  in others they do but when the position is queried the value is incorrect.    The issue doesn't not appear to be related to the nested-ness of PROTO files as previously thought  chipping away at the example mentioned in #3036 revealed that the MRE is just having a simple structure like   ```  DEF OUTER_NODE Transform {    children [      DEF INNER_NODE Transform {            }    ]  }  ```    In this case  the objects return to their initial position but after a reset their position values are incorrect. Similar situations to `T { T {} }` that also fail are: `T { S {} }`  `G { T { S { } } }`  `S { T { S { } } }`   and `S { T { T { } } }`    Specifically  what appears to be failing is the following condition:  - pick one of the structures mentioned above  let's call the inner node INNER and the outer OUTER.  - get their position: `positions_A`  - move the OUTER (for example using `set_sf_vec3f`)  - get their positions: `positions_B`    So far so good  the INNER is translated as well.    - reset and get the positions: `position_C`. This should be equal to `positions_A` but **isn't.**  - move the OUTER (for example using `set_sf_vec3f`)  - get their positions: `positions_D`. This should be equal to `position_B` and **it is**.    So the issue really is just the first value after the reset.

Title: Add Contact Points Tracking
Body: Similar to #2279 we want to provide an API function for contact points tracking.    This PR adds the following API functions:  - `wb_supervisor_node_enable_contact_point_tracking(WbNodeRef node  int sampling_period  bool include_descendants)`  - `wb_supervisor_node_disable_contact_point_tracking(WbNodeRef node  bool include_descendants)`  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points(WbNodeRef node  bool include_descendants  int *size)`    The `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points` function is a substitute for:  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_point`  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_point_node`  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_number_of_contact_points`    Therefore  these functions are deprecated.    - Tracking    - [x] Basic implementation    - Add support for other languages:      - [x] C++      - [x] Python      - [x] Java      - [x] Matlab      - [x] ROS    - [x] Documentation    - [x] Tests    - [x] ROS tests    - [x] Controller.def + WbLanguage.cpp  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points`    - [x] Basic implementation    - Add support for other languages:      - [x] C++      - [x] Python      - [x] Java      - [x] Matlab      - [x] ROS    - [x] Documentation    - [x] Tests    - [x] ROS tests    - [x] Controller.def + WbLanguage.cpp  - [x] Changelog  - Verify     - [ ] Matlab `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points`  - Non related fixes    - [x] Change the ROS sampling_period type for pose tracking    - [x] Fix pose and field tracking reset handling     - [x] Ignore `wb_supervisor_node_set_joint_position`     - [x] Change Python API to return an object instead of dictionary    **Documentation**    https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=feature-contact-point-tracking#wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points    **Development Scenario**    ```  #VRML_SIM R2021b utf8  WorldInfo {    basicTimeStep 16    coordinateSystem "NUE"  }  Viewpoint {    orientation 0.2744370696263734 -0.9240498909372512 -0.2661129344352567 4.66421960062771    position 3.2657338363728203 2.5300277265960878 0.4360826908960025  }  TexturedBackground {  }  TexturedBackgroundLight {  }  Floor {  }  WoodenBox {  }  DEF BOX WoodenBox {    translation 0 1.31 0.28    name "wooden box(1)"    mass 1  }  Robot {    controller "contacttracking"    supervisor TRUE  }  ```    ```python  from controller import Supervisor  robot = Supervisor()  use_new_api = True    timestep = int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())  box = robot.getFromDef('BOX')  box.enableContactPointsTracking(timestep)    while robot.step(timestep) != -1:      if use_new_api:          print(box.getContactPoints())      else:          n_points = box.getNumberOfContactPoints()          for i in range(n_points):              print(f'#{i}: {box.getContactPoint(i)}')              print(f'#{i}: {box.getContactPointNode(i)}')  ```    ```java  import com.cyberbotics.webots.controller.Supervisor;  import com.cyberbotics.webots.controller.Node;  import com.cyberbotics.webots.controller.ContactPoint;    public class contacttracking_java {    public static void main(String[] args) {      Supervisor robot = new Supervisor();        int timeStep = (int) Math.round(robot.getBasicTimeStep());        Node box = robot.getFromDef("BOX");            while (robot.step(timeStep) != -1){        ContactPoint[] points = box.getContactPoints(false);        for (int i = 0; i < points.length; i++) {          System.out.println(points[i].getNodeId());          System.out.println(points[i].getPoint()[1]);          }      }    }  }  ```

Title: Conversion of Lua PROTO files to JavaScript
Body: **Description**  This PR contains the conversion of all PROTO files from Lua to JavaScript. When the two PROTO are somewhat similar  the review is fairly easy but  for those where the two versions are significantly different it might be easier to open them in dummy world and play with them to see if something breaks.    For the `WbQjsFile` module  the functions I exposed were the minimal I needed for the conversion. So  I don't know if this module should be more complex than that (or something more generic). Since removing/changing these functions becomes harder after publishing (for retro-compatibility reasons)  it's worth deciding now.    Mostly complex/long ones & a couple simple ones that are important:    1. projects/objects/road/protos/AddLanesRoadSegment.proto  2. projects/objects/geometries/protos/TexturedParallelepiped.proto  3. projects/samples/contests/robocup/protos/RobocupGoal.proto  4. projects/objects/trees/protos/Forest.proto  5. projects/samples/robotbenchmark/pit_escape/protos/Pit.proto  6. projects/objects/floors/protos/CircleArena.proto  7. projects/objects/road/protos/Road.proto  8. projects/default/protos/SumoInterface.proto  9. Title: Fix regeneration of a PROTO boundingObject
Body: **Fixes**  Fixes #3215 - second example.    **Description**  The MRE is a proto such as this:    ```  #VRML_SIM R2021b utf8    PROTO Test [    field SFFloat    height          2       # Defines the height of the pipe.  ]  {    %{ local a = fields.height.value; }%    Group { # set of boxes      children [          Transform {            children [              Box {                size %{= a }% %{= a }% %{= a }%              }            ]          }      ]    }  }  ```   When the user changes a parameter from the interface  it triggers a regeneration because this field is a template regenerator. As this PROTO is used in the `boundingObject`  and its parent is of type `Solid` it enters [this](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/868b331bb7d29cc2ceed96233dd35c2752f1c84a/src/webots/nodes/utils/WbTemplateManager.cpp#L338-L340) condition. However  when it searches for the corresponding node in the parent fields (or rather  it requests its `nodeIndex`)  it does so in the children field instead of the `boundingObject` field hence failing the assertion since it cannot find it there.

Title: Drastically reduce package size
Body: Following up #2591  this PR introduces Webots URLs. Webots URLs can be used in a world file to specify textures  meshes  sounds  etc. in a similar way as the https URLs introduced in #2591. Webots URLs come as an alternative to relative or absolute file references and identify a unique file in the Webots package.  A Webots URL has the following form: `webots://` following by a file path relative to `WEBOTS_HOME`.  For example: [webots://projects/samples/geometries/worlds/textures/webots_box.png](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cyberbotics/webots/R2021a/projects/samples/geometries/worlds/textures/water_flow.jpg)    When releasing a new webots package  all world and proto files will be processed and all `webots://` URLs will be replaced with their equivalent `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cyberbotics/webots/` URL  so that all the resources files (textures  meshes  sounds  etc.) can be omitted from the distributed package. This will significantly reduce the size of the Webots packages.    Released version will use the GitHub tag to refer to resources  e.g.  R2021a  R2021a-rev1  R2021b  etc.  Nightly builds cannot use the GitHub tag for nightly builds because these tags are destroyed after 3 days. So  instead  they should use the commit sha.    - [x] Implement support for `webots://` URLs in Webots (useful only for Webots developers who checked out the webots repo).  - [ ] ~Add a "Download all resources for offline use" menu item (will download all resources in the cache of Webots).~  - [x] Replace the file URLs with `webots://` in all world files.  - [x] Replace the file URLs with `webots://` in all proto files.      The following protos were converted manually as the script failed because of LUA code:      - SimpleBuilding      - PublicToilet      - SimpleTree      The following protos were skipped as the script failed because of LUA code  but no modifications was needed:      - DirectionalPanel      - ProtoMismatchFieldType (tests folder)  - [x] Replace the file URLs also in the webots_ros submodule. See https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros/pull/59  - [x] Replace the file URLs also in the webots_ros2 repo. See https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros2/pull/233  - [x] Replace the file URLs also in the webots-project. See https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots-projects/pull/4  - [x] Change the export of .x3d files to use `webots://` urls when possible.  - [x] Adapt webotsJS to support `webots://`  - [x] Replace the `webots://` of all world and proto files in the distribution.  - [x] Remove the resources files from the distribution.  - [x] Measure the resulting size of the new webots packages: on Windows  the new package is 0.99 GB instead of 1.64 GB.      Other ideas to reduce the package size:    - on Windows  remove the mingw32 binaries.  - remove the offline documentation  replace it with online documentation only.  - remove the e-puck cross-compiler → move it to a different repo.  - use EXTERNPROTO to move proto files outside of the distribution.  - move projects (worlds  protos  controllers) outside of the distribution.

Title: Robocup controllers
Body: This PR aims at creating webots Robocup controllers for players that will run a TCP/IP server  send and receive protobuf3 messages to/from the actual robot controllers running a remote machine.  The amount of data sent is limited to 100 MB/s per team  computed on a time window of 1 second.  Data packets over this quota will be dropped.    - [x] Add protobuf3 dependency on Windows  Linux and macOS.  - [x] Implement protobuf3 messaging with a sample client program.  - [x] Fix proto tests that were conflicting with `.proto` protobuf files.  - [x] Implement the quota system.  - [x] Reject controller connections from non-authorized hosts.  - [x] Add a basic referee that setups the game from json files  including field size.  - [x] Referee automatically launches GameController.  - [x] Referee send clock messages to GameController.     The protobuf3 [messages](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cyberbotics/webots/feature-robocup-controllers/projects/samples/contests/robocup/controllers/player/messages.proto) should be sent/received over a socket connection to the simulation machine on a port corresponding to each player.

Title: Feature enu geometries
Body: **Description**  Convert the geometries to be z-aligned    **Tasks**  Add the list of tasks of this PR.    - [x] Convert cylinder    - [x] Convert capsule    - [x] Convert cone    - [x] Convert plane    - [x] Convert elevation grid    - [x] Change doc    - [x] Verify webotsJS (if you want to test it  you have to compile wren with Emscripten and change index.html and WebStreaming.js to point to the local files)    - [x] Adapt the tests      **Additional detail**    There is a script that can convert automatically worlds (scripts/converter/convert_geometries.py).  But it has some known limitations:    - It cannot convert protos  - If there is a DEF geometry that is use in a bounding object and there is already a transform in the bounding object  we need to convert it manually. Because the script add an additional transform to the geometry and become the DEF node  so we would have two Transform in the bounding object  which is forbiden.  - You need to convert by hand the following parameters of ElevationGrid:    -  zDimension -> yDimension    -  zSpacing -> ySpacing    - Add a translation on the upper transform of value -(yDimension -1) * ySpacing either on the negative y (if ENU) or positive z (NUE)    - Inverse the lines of the height     - Rotation the elevation grid by (1 0 0 -1.57)  - If a plane is scaled by a transform  you have to invert y and z scale. You also need to rotate it by (1 0 0 -1.57) (even if it does not have a scale)  - Sometimes the resulting rotation is weird when squashing transforms

Body: This PR aims at fixing the tests_sources CI test on the master branch.  It seems the newest version of cppcheck has problems with the `RELATIVE` and `ABSOLUTE` keywords.

Title: Merge master into develop
Body: **Description**  No conflicts.

Title: Merge develop into feature enu plan
Body: **Description**  Conflicts:    - `WbSphere.cpp` L375-376

Title: fix issue with python3X_path for Windows installation from sources
Body: **Description**  Makefile of controller was failling because for Windows it tries to compile even if the `PYTHON3X_HOME` was not defined (for python 3.7  3.8 or 3.9).    This PR add checks to avoid to compile if those paths are not defined.
